From: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
Date: Sat, 04 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: ethernet: qualcomm: ppe: offload netfilter flowtables

Bind netfilter flowtable offload blocks to the PPE port net devices
through ndo_setup_tc(TC_SETUP_FT) and translate the offloaded rules to
the L3 flow engine.

An offloaded rule maps to a next hop entry carrying the egress port,
the destination MAC rewrite, the egress VLAN of a VLAN push action and
the NAT addresses, plus a flow entry carrying the 5-tuple and the
translated L4 port. The router MAC table is maintained from the source
MAC rewrite of the rules: the egress source MAC of one direction is
the MAC the reverse direction ingresses on, so a connection offloaded
in both directions installs all the router MACs it needs. The egress
L3 interfaces, indexed by port, provide the source MAC rewrite and the
routing enable of each port, keyed off the same rewrite action.

Only IPv4 TCP and UDP flows with at most one NAT direction are
offloaded; everything else, including VLAN-tagged ingress, stays on
the software flowtable path, as do flow misses of offloaded
connections. Public SNAT addresses and router MACs are refcounted
scarce resources (16 and 8 entries); exhaustion falls back to
software. Both tables are backed by a common refcounted-table helper,
struct ppe_ft_ref, which keeps the entry scan and the reference
bookkeeping in one place. The host table entry of a destination is
shared by every flow routed to it and refcounted the same way, deleted
only with the last of them - a per-flow delete of the host would
otherwise strip the entry a sibling flow still needs. Flow statistics
come from the per-flow hit counters, keeping the flowtable entries
alive while traffic flows in hardware.

A flow whose hardware delete fails keeps forwarding, so its next hop
and address table slots are leaked rather than reused under the live
entry.

Signed-off-by: Kenneth Kasilag <kenneth@kasilag.me>
